<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-713-815  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 713 815.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  Dec 10 1990 v7 n15 p90(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Connecting LANs to hosts. (local area networks) (part of a specialsection on network integration)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ragucci, Richard J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Local area networks (LAN) are being assigned the task of providingconnectivity between the desktop and corporate computingenvironments.andP;  This connectivity is established through one offive basic methods: asynchronous links that connect microcomputersdirectly to the host, LAN gateways with dedicated microcomputersacting as links, a direct token-ring link, Transmission ControlProtocol/Internet Protocol (TCP/IP) serving as a common protocolon both LAN and host, or Network File System (NFS), providing adistributed file system and transparent access to the host.andO;Systems integrators must determine which solution will be optimumfor a given user by consideration of the host, its operatingenvironment and physical location; the network operating system orsystems, the network wiring scheme, user requirements andapplications, and the client's budget.andP;  Configuration of aLAN-to-host system should be well thought out early in the designstages of the network.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     System DesignConnectivityLocal Area NetworksGuidelinesMicrocomputers.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Various methods of microcomputer-to-host connectivity. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>